<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="390" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1221]" pageId="2" pageNumber="390">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,367,392]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="390" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Alves &amp; Santos &amp; Nessimian, 2018" authorityName="Alves &amp; Santos &amp; Nessimian" authorityYear="2018" box="[325,547,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="390" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caatinga" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[325,547,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="390">Smicridea caatinga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[557,650,367,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="390">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[557,650,367,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="390" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
belongs to the 
<emphasis box="[833,847,368,391]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="390">S</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1920" box="[865,1042,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="390" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigripennis" subGenus="Smicridea">
(
<emphasis box="[874,888,368,391]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="390">S</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[914,1042,368,391]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="390">nigripennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Group (
<bibRefCitation author="Flint, O. S. Jr." box="[1141,1275,367,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="390" pagination="1 - 65" refId="ref5603" refString="Flint, O. S. Jr. (1974 a) Studies of Neotropical caddisflies, XVII: The genus Smicridea from North and Central America (Trichoptera: Hydropsychidae). Smithsonian Contributions in Zoology, 167, 1 - 65. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.167" type="journal article" year="1974">Flint 1974a</bibRefCitation>
) due to some characteristics of the phallic apparatus, as the basal half of the phallus open ventrally with the sclerotized part very much enlarged, the apical half open posterodorsally with spines extending from the endotheca, and with the lateral and ventral regions produced into lobes and spines. Among the species in this group, the new species is closest to 
<emphasis box="[1415,1429,476,499]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="390">S</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis box="[160,174,512,535]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="390">S</emphasis>
.) 
<emphasis box="[199,331,512,536]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="390">franciscana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Rocha, I. C. &amp; Dumas, L. L. &amp; Nessimian, J. L." box="[339,727,511,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="390" pagination="423 - 430" refId="ref6368" refString="Rocha, I. C., Dumas, L. L. &amp; Nessimian, J. L. (2016) Three new species and a new record of Smicridea McLachlan 1871 (Trichoptera: Hydropsychidae) from Minas Gerais state, Brazil. Zootaxa, 4107 (3), 423 - 430. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4107.3.10" type="journal article" year="2016">
<collectingRegion box="[339,413,511,536]" country="Uruguay" name="Rocha" pageId="2" pageNumber="390">Rocha</collectingRegion>
, Dumas &amp; Nessimian 2016
</bibRefCitation>
due to the shape of segment X, which is divided apically into two lobes, and the phallus with one pair of endothecal spines directed posterad. However, the new species can be easily distinguished from this and all other species in the subgenus by the phallus having one pair of dorsal mesolateral lobes covered by short setae, and one pair of ventrolateral sclerotized process. Additionally, when phallus is everted, on the apex of the apical section are a characteristic pair of dorsal membranous lobes, a lateral pair of lobes with small protuberances, and a large ventral membranous lobe.
</paragraph>
